problem: What is $\dbinom{n}{n}$ for any positive integer $n$?
solution: $\dbinom{n}{n}=\dfrac{n!}{n!0!}=\boxed{1}$.  Also, there is only one way to choose $n$ objects out of $n$, which is simply choosing all of them.
model_solution:
Step 1:  Recall the formula for $\dbinom{n}{r}$, which is $\dfrac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}$.
Step 2:  $\dbinom{n}{n} = \dfrac{n!}{n!(n-n)!}$
Step 3:  $\dfrac{n!}{n!(n-n)!} = \dfrac{n!}{n!0!}$
Step 4:  $\dfrac{n!}{n!0!} = \dfrac{1}{0!}$
Step 5:  $\dfrac{1}{0!} = 1$
Step 6:  By the definition of 0!, $0! = 1$
Step 7:  Since $0! = 1$, then $\dfrac{1}{0!} = \dfrac{1}{1} = 1$ is valid.
Step 8:  $\dbinom{n}{n} = 1$
Step 9:  By definition, $\dbinom{n}{n}$ represents the number of ways to choose $n$ objects from a set of $n$ distinct objects.
Step 10:  Since $\dbinom{n}{n} = 1$, there is only one way to choose $n$ objects from a set of $n$ distinct objects, namely, all $n$ objects.
